This is a good example of a frustrating request for help. It starts out assuming the reader knows what the poster knows, and has access to all the code. It only listed a portion of the code, because the bug couldn't have been in any of the other code (or could it?). Then the solution doesn't explain what the problem was, and the original post was modified to remove code after the solution was posted. The poster seemed only interested in solving the problem, nothing more. This kind of response won't encourage help in the future.<br /><br />Recommended reading: <a href="http://catb.org/esr/faqs/smart-questions.html" class="postlink">How to ask questions the smart way</a><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Fri Aug 27, 2010 7:58 am</p><hr />
