<div class="quotetitle">strat wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G43rWW0kRJw<br /><br />With attribute writing minus nametable writing<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoTIABWVEo0">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoTIABWVEo0</a><!-- m --><br /><br />The other nametable flashes on and off while it scrolls right.  No glitches scrolling left.  Here's what is seemingly ruled out:<br />- Fat NMI.  Even without the nametable update, the attribute update still causes the glitch.  (Updating the nametable minus the attribute is fine).<br />- Unintended write to bit 0 of $2000.  Obviously the glitch would still happen in any case.<br />- Badly timed sprite 0.  Again, I'd expect this to happen even without updating the attribute table.<br /><br />I narrowed it to the PPUADDR write in the attribute update.  This is kind of hair pulling because it's not apparent what is different about the nametable update.  Because PPUADDR also affects the scrolling here's the attribute updating routine in case someone catches it.<br /><br />(Forgot to mention:  Everything is peachy keen without a sprite zero hit.)<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Write_Attr_Side:<br />   <br />   lda prev_col<br />   lsr<br />   lsr<br />   tax<br />   clc<br />   adc #$C0<br />   tay<br />@Loop:<br />   bit PPUSTAT<br />   lda hi_attr_table<br />   sta PPUADDR<br />   tya<br />   sta PPUADDR<br />   <br />   clc<br />   adc #$08<br />   tay<br />   <br />   lda attr_buffer,X<br />   sta PPUDATA<br />   <br />   txa<br />   clc<br />   adc #$08<br />   tax<br />   <br />   cpx #$40<br />   bcc @Loop<br />   <br />   rts<br /></div><br /></div><br /><br /><br />I tried debuggin this code manually and there seems to be nothing wrong with this piece of code.<br /><br />saw the first video in slow motion and it revealed that at one point the other name table is displayed in full i.e. it seems somewhere down the line the last bit(s) of PPUCTRL is/are getting corrupted.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4104">Nadia</a> — Fri Aug 27, 2010 12:56 am</p><hr />
